V'''L. T. F. Gamut''' was a collective [[pseudonym]] for the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[logic]]ians [[Johan van Benthem (logician)|Johan van Benthem]], [[Jeroen Groenendijk]], [[Dick de Jongh]], [[Martin Stokhof]] and [[Henk Verkuyl]].<ref>Preface to ''Logic, Language and Meaning'', by L. T. F. Gamut, University of Chicago Press, 1991.</ref>\u000a\u000aGamut stands for the Dutch universities of [[University of Groningen|Groningen]] ('''G'''), [[University of Amsterdam|Amsterdam]] ('''am'''), and [[Utrecht University|Utrecht]] ('''ut'''), then the affiliations of the authors.<ref>{{jstor|2275619}}</ref> The initials L. T. F. stand for the discussed topics, respectively, Logic (Dutch: '''''L'''ogica''), Language (Dutch: '''''T'''aal'') and Philosophy (Dutch: '''''F'''ilosofie'').\u000a\u000a== References ==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==Publications==\u000a*''Logica, taal en betekenis I: inleiding in de logica'', [[Het Spectrum]], 1982. {{Nl icon}}\u000a*''Logica, taal en betekenis II: intensionele logica en logische grammatica'', Het Spectrum, 1982. {{Nl icon}}\u000a*''Logic, Language and Meaning, Volume I: Introduction to Logic'', [[University of Chicago]] Press, 1991. Translation and revision of ''Logica, taal en betekenis I''.\u000a*''Logic, Language and Meaning, Volume II: Intensional Logic and Logical Grammar'', University of Chicago Press, 1991. Translation and revision of ''Logica, taal en betekenis II''.\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Gamut, LTF}}\u000a[[Category:Dutch logicians]]\u000a[[Category:Dutch philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Pseudonymous mathematicians]]\u000a[[Category:Academic shared pseudonyms]]
